This species may be readily known by its elongate, parallel shape and very short antennae, the elytra with only eight rows of very coarse punctures, their apices separately rounded and very finely serrulate, the second, fourth, and sixth inter· spaces strongly costate throughout. The penultimate joints of the antennae are closely articulated and transverse. 0. parallelus closely resembles Uroplata limbata, Baly, but in that insect the apical five joints of the antennae are consolidated into a single plece.
